comments.body:
It seems to me that production code never actually calls `AddFlags` with a 0 value â€” we are always setting `DIRTY`, even when `FRESH` is set.
Therefore, it would make sense to change `AddFlags` from using a custom `uint8_t flags` parameter (which is always `DIRTY` and sometimes `FRESH` in practice, and only called with a `0` in tests) to using a freshness parameter, such as `SetDirtyAndFresh(CoinsCachePair& self, CoinsCachePair& sentinel, bool is_fresh = false)`.

This change would allow us to remove a lot of invalid test cases like this one (i.e. where flag is 0 or non-dirty).

As you've also mentioned, this would also allow us to remove the internal flags entirely.
Instead of exposing the flags, we could simplify the implementation like this:
```C++
inline bool IsDirty() const noexcept
{
    assert(!m_next == !m_prev);
    return !!m_next;
}
inline bool IsFresh() const noexcept { return m_is_fresh; }
```

